  "image_url": "https://cdn.kirtansewa.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/21222128/Bhai-Amrik-Singh-Gurdaspuri-2.jpg",
  "body": [
    "Bhai Amrik Singh Ji was born on 13 th April 1958 at the village of Harpura, located in the Batala tehsil of Gurdaspur, Punjab. He attended the Senior Secondary School of Harpura Dhandoi, and completed his matriculation studies. During his formative years, he developed a profound affinity for music. This led him to pick up the traditional instrument, ‘tumbi’, which he would use as accompaniment while singing Punjabi folk songs. Alongside his formal education, he also learned ‘Gurbani Santhiya’ and would regularly partake in ‘Akhand Paath’ duties.",
    "Upon completing his studies, he contemplated formal music education. This prompted him to learn Kirtan at Gurdwara Nanakmatta Sahib, Uttrakhand. Subsequent to this, he still yearned for more and this thirst for knowledge led him to Bombay. Here, he came under the tutelage of Ustad Joginder Singh ‘Jogi’, who was a well-respected and knowledgeable musician. Following an enriching period of learning Kirtan from Ustad Joginder Singh Ji, he secured positions as Hazoori Raagi in various locations outside Punjab, including Nagpur, Pune and the historical Gurdwara Imli Sahib in Indore, Madhya Pardesh.",
    "In 1990, he began serving as Hazoori Raagi in Gurdwara Singh Sabha Raja Park in Jaipur, Rajasthan. He still harbored a desire to learn more, and the move to Jaipur paved the way for an invaluable opportunity to advance his musical expertise. Here, he met the renowned ghazal duo, Ustad Ahmed Hussain and Mohammed Hussain. He spent 2 years refining his skills under their guidance.",
    "He embarked on his first international tour to Canada in 1995, followed by subsequent travels to England and the United States of America. Presently, he is settled in New York and serves as Hazoori Raagi at Gurdwara Baba Makhan Shah Lubana Sikh Center. Accompanying him in his ‘jatha’ are Bhai Nirman Singh and Bhai Satnam Singh.",
    "If anyone has more recordings of Bhai Amrik Singh Ji to share, please contact us."
  ],
